result.execSummary:
The defendant Lupe T. Medina was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Burglary-Building or Dwelling [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.10(1m)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

09:32 AM  Court in session.  Case called.  Appearances given.  
Parties are appearing by phone due to COVID-19.  
ADA Matthew Leusink appears by phone.  
Probation Agent Heather Damask and Deft Lupe Medina appear by phone.  
Matter is before the court on a probation review hearing primarily on restitution.  
Court received a email from victim.  Probation Agent has seen the e-mail.  
Agent is not requesting that Mr. Medina be extended since he is currently on an extension for not paying restitution in full.  He has made a few payments.  Agent understands victim's frustration.  Deft has restitution on other cases that have victims.  The balance for this victim is $4,078.60.  Agent gives summary as to restitution owed to multiple victims.  When deft makes a payment, it is divided among to all 4 victims.  This year deft has only made one payment of $30.00.  In 2018, he made 5 payments.  Response by Mr. Medina to Court's question as to why he hasn't paid more.  Deft says he has a child and for awhile there, his spouse was not working.  His hours have been recently cut at work due to COVID-19.  9:39 am  Response by Atty Leusink.  He believes probation should be extended for a year.  Agent Damask has nothing further to add nor does Mr. Medina.  9:40 am  Court is aware the probation is not to be used as a collection agency.  Court does not believe making 1 payment since January is a good faith effort and court realizes times are tough starting in March.  Court extends probation for 2 years.  If deft can pay off restitution, probation can be terminated.  Deft required to make a good faith effort each and every month.  Agent to submit Order for extension.  9:43 am  Court in recess.
